n%20May%202%2C%202023%2C%20Pauline%20Stensgar%2C%20of%20Keller%2C%20Washington%20State%2C%20died%20at%20the%20age%20of%2096.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.spokesman.com%2Fstories%2F2023%2Fmay%2F05%2Flast-fluent-speaker-of-nxamxcin-language-dies-at-9%2F%5C%22%3EHer%20language%20died%20with%20her%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Ci%3EThe%20Spokesman-Review%3C%2Fi%3E%C2%A0in%20Spokane%20reported%20she%20was%20the%20last%20fluent%20speaker%20of%20the%C2%A0%3Ci%3En%CC%93xa%CA%94m%CC%93xc%CC%8Ci%CC%81n%CC%93%3C%2Fi%3E%C2%A0(pronounced%20%E2%80%98in-ha-um-cheen%E2%80%99)%20language.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIt%20was%20a%20language%20that%20had%20been%20spoken%20by%20some%20groups%20of%20Native%20Americans%20in%20the%20Washington%20State%20region.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThanks%20to%20Stensgar%E2%80%99s%20love%20for%20her%20language%2C%20it%20is%20not%20completely%20lost%20to%20us.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ETogether%20with%20Christopher%20Parkin%2C%20the%20principal%20of%20the%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22http%3A%2F%2Fsalishschoolofspokane.org%2F%5C%22%3ESalish%20School%20of%20Spokane%2C%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0Stensgar%20had%20created%20six%20textbooks%20and%20more%20than%20100%20recordings%20of%20the%20language.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAnyone%20interested%20can%20still%20learn%C2%A0%3Ci%3En%CC%93xa%CA%94m%CC%93xc%CC%8Ci%CC%81n%CC%93%3C%2Fi%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20for%20many%20extinct%20languages%2C%20we%E2%80%99re%20not%20so%20lucky.%20They%20can%20be%20lost%20to%20us%20forever.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAnd%20in%20the%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ethnologue.com%2Finsights%2Fcontinents-most-indigenous-languages%2F%5C%22%3Eparts%20of%20the%20world%20richest%20in%20languages%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20environmental%20disaster%20is%20forcing%20the%20displacement%20of%20millions%20of%20people%20%E2%80%93%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nbcnews.com%2Fnews%2Flatino%2Fmigration-indigenous-languages-going-extinct-n52731%5C%22%3Ea%20major%20trigger%20of%20language%20extinction%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELanguage%20is%20uniquely%20human%2C%20our%20cognitive%20capacities%20on%20full%20display.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEach%20of%20the%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ethnologue.com%2F%5C%22%3Emore%20than%207%2C000%20living%20languages%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0in%20the%20world%20today%20encodes%20the%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fglobal.oup.com%2Facademic%2Fproduct%2Fwhen-languages-die-9780195372069%3Fcc%3Dus%26lang%3Den%26%5C%22%3Eworldview%2C%20history%20and%20knowledge%20of%20its%20speakers%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMany%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ethnologue.com%2Fendangered-languages%2F%5C%22%3Eendangered%20languages%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%93%20those%20that%20are%20rapidly%20losing%20speakers%20%E2%80%93%20hold%20vital%20knowledge%20about%20local%20plants%2C%20including%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pnas.org%2Fsyndication%2Fdoi%2F10.1073%2Fpnas.2103683118%5C%22%3Eunique%20knowledge%20on%20these%20plants%E2%80%99%20medicinal%20uses%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThese%20languages%20also%20hold%20knowledge%20on%20animals%20and%20how%20to%20live%20sustainably%20in%20the%20local%20environment.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20means%20that%20we%20not%20only%20lose%20languages%2C%20we%20also%20lose%20knowledge%20that%20can%20help%20us%20live%20better%2C%20healthier%20and%20more%20sustainably.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWe%20lose%20languages%20when%20speakers%20no%20longer%20pass%20these%20languages%20on%20to%20their%20children.%20This%20often%20happens%20when%20speakers%20of%20minority%20languages%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmufwene.uchicago.edu%2Fpublications%2FHOW_LANGUAGES_DIE.pdf%5C%22%3Eswitch%20to%20languages%20that%20are%20economically%20more%20advantageous%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMigration%20plays%20a%20large%20role%20in%20this.%20For%20example%2C%20most%20second-generation%20immigrants%20to%20the%20US%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F2673171%5C%22%3Espeak%20English%20fluently%2C%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0but%20not%20their%20parents%E2%80%99%20languages.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEnglish%20is%20economically%20and%20culturally%20beneficial%20to%20them%2C%20but%20their%20parents%E2%80%99%20languages%20are%20not.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fflo.uri.sh%2Fvisualisation%2F14688624%2Fembed%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Interactive%20or%20visual%20content%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%20noreferrer%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpublic.flourish.studio%2Fvisualisation%2F14688624%2F%3Futm_source%3Dembed%26utm_campaign%3Dvisualisation%2F14688624%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_top%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20alt%3D%5C%22Made%20with%20Flourish%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fpublic.flourish.studio%2Fresources%2Fmade_with_flourish.svg%5C%22%3E%20%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20look%20at%20where%20the%20most%20Indigenous%20languages%20are%20endangered%20reveals%20the%20impact%20of%20previous%20migrations.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%202021%2C%2098%20percent%20of%20Indigenous%20languages%20in%20the%20US%20and%2089%20percent%20of%20Indigenous%20languages%20in%20Australia%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ethnologue.com%2Finsights%2Fhow-many-languages-endangered%2F%5C%22%3Ewere%20endangered%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBoth%20countries%20have%20a%20colonial%20history%20and%20have%20seen%20mass%20immigration%20from%20Europe%20in%20previous%20centuries.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThese%20earlier%20migrations%20affect%20Indigenous%20languages%20to%20this%20day%20%E2%80%93%20we%20continue%20losing%20languages%20in%20these%20countries%20because%20speakers%20no%20longer%20pass%20them%20on%20to%20future%20generations%20and%20switch%20to%20English%20instead.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESo%2C%20today%E2%80%99s%20migration%20will%20likely%20be%20tomorrow%E2%80%99s%20language%20loss.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EForced%20migration%20plays%20a%20large%20role%20in%20current%20migration%20patterns.%20According%20to%20the%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.unhcr.org%2Fglobal-trends-report-2022%5C%22%3EGlobal%20Trends%20Report%202022%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20more%20than%20108%20million%20people%20were%20forcibly%20displaced%20in%202022.%20About%2061%20million%20of%20them%20were%20displaced%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.internal-displacement.org%2Fglobal-report%2Fgrid2023%2F%5C%22%3Ewithin%20their%20own%20countries%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMore%20than%20half%20of%20those%20internally%20displaced%20had%20to%20leave%20their%20homes%20because%20of%20environmental%20disasters%2C%20such%20as%20floods%20and%20storms.%20The%20remaining%20people%20were%20internally%20displaced%20by%20conflict%20and%20violence.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAlmost%20all%20internal%20displacement%20in%20Europe%20and%20Central%20Asia%20in%202022%20was%20due%20to%20conflict%20and%20violence.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20contrast%2C%20almost%20all%20internal%20displacement%20in%20South%20Asia%2C%20East%20Asia%20and%20the%20Pacific%20was%20caused%20by%20weather-related%20disasters%2C%20such%20as%20floods%20and%20storms.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESome%20of%20the%20most%20linguistically%20diverse%20countries%20are%20in%20South%20Asia%2C%20East%20Asia%20and%20the%20Pacific%2C%20those%20regions%20particularly%20affected%20by%20environmental%20disasters.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EPapua%20New%20Guinea%20has%20at%20least%20nine%20million%20inhabitants.%20Between%20them%20they%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ethnologue.com%2Fcountry%2FPG%2F%5C%22%3Espeak%20839%20different%20languages%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0with%20313%20of%20those%20languages%20endangered.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20300%2C000%20inhabitants%20of%20Vanuatu%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ethnologue.com%2Fcountry%2FVU%2F%5C%22%3Espeak%20108%20different%20languages%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20of%20which%20more%20than%20half%20are%20endangered.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ethnologue.com%2Fcountry%2FID%2F%5C%22%3EIndonesia%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0has%20another%20704%20living%20languages%2C%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ethnologue.com%2Fcountry%2FIN%2F%5C%22%3EIndia%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0has%20424%2C%20and%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ethnologue.com%2Fcountry%2FPH%2F%5C%22%3Ethe%20Philippines%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0has%20175.%20Almost%20half%20of%20the%20languages%20spoken%20in%20these%20three%20countries%20are%20endangered.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMore%20than%20one%20third%20of%20the%20languages%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Funesdoc.unesco.org%2Fark%3A%2F48223%2Fpf0000192416%5C%22%3Econsidered%20endangered%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0are%20spoken%20in%20those%20five%20countries%20alone.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20large%20numbers%20of%20already%20endangered%20languages%20combined%20with%20the%20large%20numbers%20of%20people%20displaced%20by%20environmental%20disasters%20make%20South%20Asia%2C%20East%20Asia%20and%20the%20Pacific%20particularly%20vulnerable%20to%20future%20language%20loss.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMany%20of%20these%20endangered%20languages%20are%20spoken%20in%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Funesdoc.unesco.org%2Fark%3A%2F48223%2Fpf0000187026%5C%22%3Ea%20small%20geographic%20area%C2%A0%3C%2Fa%3Eand%20have%C2%A0%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fnews%2Fdatablog%2F2011%2Fapr%2F15%2Flanguage-extinct-endangered%5C%22%3Eonly%20a%20few%20hundred%20speakers%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0left.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIf%20speakers%20of%20those%20languages%20leave%20their%20small%20communities%20and%20scatter%20%E2%80%93%20for%20whatever%20reasons%20%E2%80%93%20it%20becomes%20less%20likely%20that%20they%20will%20pass%20on%20these%20languages%20to%20future%20generations.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EOutside%20their%20small%20communities%2C%20these%20languages%20are%20likely%20to%20have%20little%20economic%20and%20cultural%20value.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20problem%20with%20forced%20migration%20is%20that%20people%20lose%20their%20community.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESo%2C%20lots%20of%20the%20things%20that%20people%20propose%20to%20preserve%20languages%20%E2%80%93%20like%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcompass.onlinelibrary.wiley.com%2Fdoi%2Ffull%2F10.1111%2Fj.1749-818X.2007.00004.x%5C%22%3Eensuring%20communities%20remain%20together%2C%20have%20a%20viable%20environment%20to%20live%20in%20and%20ways%20of%20making%20a%20living%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%93%20do%20not%20necessarily%20apply%20here.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThere%20are%20many%20reasons%20for%20language%20loss%2C%20and%20migration%20is%20only%20one%20part%20of%20the%20puzzle.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20in%20those%20parts%20of%20the%20world%20where%20we%20find%20many%20of%20the%20endangered%20languages%2C%20environmental%20disasters%20are%20a%20major%20driving%20force%20of%20migration.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAnd%20this%20forced%20migration%20%E2%80%93%20and%20subsequent%20threat%20to%20languages%20%E2%80%93%20has%20the%20potential%20to%20accelerate.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftwitter.com%2Fanouschkafoltz%5C%22%3E%3Ci%3EAnouschka%20Foltz%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Ci%3E%C2%A0is%20an%20associate%20professor%20in%20English%20linguistics%20in%20the%20Department%20of%20English%20Studies%20at%20the%20University%20of%20Graz%20in%20Austria.%20Before%20coming%20to%20Graz%20she%20was%20a%20lecturer%20in%20psycholinguistics%20at%20Bangor%20University%20in%20Wales.%20Her%20research%20is%20in%20the%20area%20of%20psycholinguistics%2C%20and%20her%20work%20focuses%20on%20adult%20language%20processing%2C%20L1%20and%20L2%20language%20acquisition%20as%20well%20as%20multilingualism.%20She%20is%20also%20interested%20in%20language%20rights%20and%20access%20to%20language.%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Ci%3EOriginally%20published%20under%C2%A0%3C%2Fi%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcreativecommons.org%2Flicenses%2Fby%2F4.0%2F%5C%22%3E%3Ci%3ECreative%20Commons%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Ci%3E%C2%A0by%C2%A0%3C%2Fi%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2F360info.org%2F%5C%22%3E%3Ci%3E360info%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Ci%3E%E2%84%A2.%3C%2Fi%3